  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The Swallow
  author: Lee Seung-so
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The painted pavilion stretches deep, its curtain valance hangs low.
    In pairs they fly, in pairs they call, in pairs they nest and rest.
    Beyond the gate the green willows see spring's evening wind,
    And by the pool the tender grass lies lost in gentle rain.

    At times they chase the butterflies through bamboo-covered slopes,
    All day they peck the muddy ground to gather for their nest.
    Having found a place to settle, who would dare despise them?
    Year after year their young ones grow with wings at last complete.
  footnotes:
    - The poem celebrates the swallow as a symbol of contentment and devotion—finding purpose in humble labor and finding dignity in familial bonds.
